INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (465, 3, '2011-01-17 04:29:11', '2011-01-17 04:29:11', '10:58 The final words of the Awards: "And thank you to God for making me an atheist." Thank you Ricky Gervais; way to go for the controversy. I''m sure Bill O''Reilly will yell at you very soon. From my comfy chair in cold, dark Wyomissing, Pennsylvania, I wish you all a pleasant evening.\n\n10:56 And <em>The Social Network </em>takes the award, its fourth win of the night.\n\n10:48 AAAAND NOW all that is left is Best Motion Picture Drama... drumroll please....\n\n10:47 Best Actor in a Motion Picture Drama goes to Colin Firth for his performance as King Edward VI in <em>The King''s Speech</em>, the film''s first win of the night.\n\n10:40 Best Motion Picture Comedy or Musical goes to <em>The Kids Are All Right</em>. Duh. This is the film''s second win of the night, along with Annette Bening''s win as Best Actress in a Motion Picture Comedy or Musical.\n\n10:35 Best Actress in a Motion Picture Drama goes to Natalie Portman for her performance as Nina in <em>Black Swan</em>, a well-deserved win for an extremely taxing role.  This is the film''s first win of the night.\n\n10:25 Best Actor in a Motion Picture Comedy or Musical goes to Paul Giamatti for his performance in <em>Barney''s Version</em>.\n\n10:20 <em>Glee</em> wins its second Golden Globe for Best Musical or Comedy TV Series, marking the show''s third win of the night, adding to the wins of Jane Lynch as Best TV Supporting Actress and Chris Colfer as Best TV Supporting Actor.\n\n10:15 Best Director for a Motion Picture goes to David Fincher for <em>The Social Network</em>, marking the third win for the film tonight, adding to Aaron Sorkin''s win for Best Motion Picture Screenplay.\n\n9:59 Robert DeNiro is presented with the Cecil B. DeMille Award.\n\n9:51 Best Supporting Actress in a Motion Picture goes to Melissa Leo for her performance as Alice Ward in <em>The Fighter</em>.\n\n9:48 Best Actor in a TV Comedy or Musical goes to Jim Parsons from<em> The Big Bang Theory.</em>\n\n9:40 Best Actress in a TV Comedy or Musical goes to Laura Linney for her performance in <em>The Big C</em>. She was not there to accept the award.\n\n9:37 Best Foreign Language Film goes to <em>In A Better World</em> from Denmark, which has not yet had a US release beyond Sundance and has otherwise enjoyed very limited worldwide penetration.  I''m sure that will change now.\n\n9:30 Best Supporting Actress in a TV Series, Mini-Series, or TV Movie goes to Jane Lynch for her performance as Sue Sylvester on <em>Glee</em>, marking the second win for the show tonight.  This comes as absolutely no surprise; Sue Sylvester has become an icon of modern American television.\n\n9:26 Best Screenplay for a Motion Picture goes to the invincible Aaron Sorkin for <em>The Social Network<span style="font-weight: normal;">, </span><span style="font-style: normal;">a deserving win amongst a field of tough competition from </span><span style="font-style: normal;"><em>Inception</em><span style="font-style: normal;">,</span> <em>127 Hours</em><span style="font-style: normal;">,</span> <em>The King''s Speech</em><span style="font-style: normal;">, and </span><em>The Kids Are All Right</em>.</span></em>\n\n9:16 Best Actress in a TV Movie or Mini-Series goes to Claire Dane for her performance in <em>Temple Grandin</em>.\n\n9:13 Best Actor in a TV Movie or Mini-Series goes to Al Pacino for his performance as Dr. Kevorkian in <em>You Don''t Know Jack</em>, marking his fourth Golden Globe win for his fifteenth nomination<strong>.</strong>\n\n9:10 I don''t usually care about what actors and actresses look like, but <a href="http://www.popeater.com/2011/01/16/helena-bonham-carter-shoes-golden-globes/" target="_blank">Helena Bonham Carter''s hair</a> makes her look like she just stepped of the set of <em>Harry Potter</em>, in which she plays Bellatrix LeStrange.\n\n9:03 Best Actress in a Motion Picture Comedy or Musical goes to Annette Bening from <em>The Kids are All Right. <span style="font-style: normal;">With two nominations in this category and two in other categories, this film is already faring well. It is the likely winner of the Best Motion Picture Comedy or Musical, as it''s really the only deserving nomination.</span></em>\n\n8:56 Best Animated Feature Film goes to <em>Toy Story 3</em>.  No surprises there, although Pixar did have some tough competition this year, especially in<em> Despicable Me</em>.\n\n8:50 Best Original Score for a Motion picture goes to Trent Reznor and Atticus Ross for their work on <em>The Social Network</em>, certainly a deserving win.\n\n8:46 Best Original Song from a Motion Picture goes to "You Haven''t Seen the Last of Me" from <em>Burlesque</em>, hopefully the only award that film will win tonight.\n\n8:38 And there you go; <em>Boardwalk Empire</em> snags the Golden Globe for Best TV Drama.\n\n8:34 Best Actor in a TV Series goes to Steve Buscemi from HBO''s exciting new show <em>Boardwalk Empire</em>, which will probably win the Golden Globe for Best TV Drama.\n\n8:24 Best Supporting Actor in TV Series, TV Movie, or Mini-Series goes to Chris Colfer, playing Kurt from <em>Glee</em>, starting off what could be another big night for the show on the right foot.\n\n8:18 Best Mini-Series or TV Movie goes to<em> Carlos</em>, which is a bit of a surprise, with the industry favorite and Critics'' Choice winner being<em> The Pacific.</em>\n\n8:10 Best TV Performance by an Actress goes to Katey Sagal from <em>Sons of Anarchy.</em> They cut off her speech oh so quickly.  Blame it on Christian Bale.\n\n8:07 - Christian Bale takes home the Best Supporting Actor award, and deservedly so.  His transformation into Dickie was absolutely incredible.  But he really needs to take on roles of a more consistent body weight.\n\n8:04 - Ricky Gervais is already offending people, targeting perhaps the two worst nominations of the year, <em>Burlesque</em> and<em> The Tourist</em>.  He also makes fun of Scientologists and gets a big "ooooh" from the audience.  Get over yourselves.', 'The 68th Annual Golden Globe Awards – Live Blog', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '462-autosave', '', '', '2011-01-17 04:29:11', '2011-01-17 04:29:11', '', 462, 'http://recess.nujigroup.com/?p=465', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
